                     <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18240114-212-off1202 t18240114-212-victim1835"></join>
                  </persName>
            .</p>
               <p>SECOND COUNT, stating it to belong to a person or persons unknown.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18240114-212-person1836">
                  JAMES 
                  SLATER
               <interp inst="t18240114-212-person1836" type="surname" value="SLATER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18240114-212-person1836" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18240114-212-person1836" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . This prisoner was also a <rs id="t18240114-212-deflabel1205" type="occupation">labourer in the Docks, and employed at the opium</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18240114-212-defend1834 t18240114-212-deflabel1205"></join>; and when I took Haywood, the prisoner immediately took his hat off, and threw two pieces of opium and a handkerchief out of his hat into the chest. I took two pieces of opium from the box, one of which I know to be one of those he threw out, they both laid loose, and the rest was closely packed.</p>
               <p>ARCHIBALD M'DONALD. I was with Slater, and saw the handkerchief and two pieces of opium in the box. I said</p>
               <p>"This is what came out of your hat;" he said, No. Slater said he saw it come from his hat. I was going to take him away; he said, I had found nothing in his possession, and at the warehouse he said only one piece belonged to him, and the other to Haywood.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. If the officer had come two hours<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182401140073"></xptr>before, they would have found the same in our possession.</p>
               <p>GUILTY. Aged 32.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18240114-212-verdict1206" type="verdictDescription">
